{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17648924","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17648924"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:59:04+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:59:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18336"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18336","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18336"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11054"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79321"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11054","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11054"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18336"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64643"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25646"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25651"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27147"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79321","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79321"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe cuboid is one of the bones in the foot.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes its location and articulation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Located anteriorly and articulates with the navicular","Located centrally and articulates with the first metatarsal","Located laterally and articulates with the calcaneus","Located medially and articulates with the talus","Located posteriorly and articulates with the tibia"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe tarsal bones form the posterior part of the foot and are crucial for foot structure and function. Among these bones is the cuboid, which plays a role in the lateral column of the foot.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe correct description is that the cuboid is \u003Cstrong\u003Elocated laterally and articulates with the calcaneus\u003C/strong\u003E. It is one of the tarsal bones on the lateral side of the foot and also articulates with the lateral cuneiform and the fourth and fifth metatarsals.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELocated medially and articulates with the talus\u003C/strong\u003E - The talus is more medial and articulates with the navicular\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELocated anteriorly and articulates with the navicular\u003C/strong\u003E - The navicular is anterior to the talus and does not articulate with the cuboid\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELocated posteriorly and articulates with the tibia\u003C/strong\u003E - The tibia articulates with the talus, not the cuboid\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELocated centrally and articulates with the first metatarsal\u003C/strong\u003E - The first metatarsal articulates with the medial cuneiform\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The cuboid is one of the tarsal bones located in the foot.","The cuboid bone is situated on the lateral side of the foot.","The cuboid articulates with the calcaneus, lateral cuneiform, and the fourth and fifth metatarsals."],"references":["Patton, K. T., \u0026 Thibodeau, G. A. (2018). Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book: Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Smith, R., \u0026 Wordsworth, P. (2016). Oxford textbook of clinical and biochemical disorders of the skeleton. Oxford University Press","Sud, A., \u0026 Ranjan, R. (2021). Textbook of Orthopaedics, 2e-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Dandy, D. J., \u0026 Edwards, D. J. (2009). Essential Orthopaedics and Trauma E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","MacGregor R, Byerly DW. Anatomy, Bony Pelvis and Lower Limb: Foot Bones. 2023 May 23. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 32491379."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64643"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18336"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64643","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64643"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-14T09:25:14+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-14T09:25:57+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11054"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79321"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"up